# Git & GitHub Homework

### Local

* Create a folder
* Initialize a git repository in the folder
* Create a couple of text files .txt
* Stage the files
* Commit the files to the repository
* Change the files
* Commit the changes

### Remote - Github

* Create new repository

### Local

* Add the github remote
* Push to the remote repository

## Further...

Investigate gitignore files.

-----------------------------------------
--------# Git & GitHub Homework #--------
-----------------------------------------
### Local

Create a folder:
- In terminal type   mkdir foldername;
- Move into the folder typing   cd foldername;
- Initialize the repository typing   git init;
- Create a couple of text files typing   touch namefile.txt namefile2.txt
    check with  git status if the files were created;
- Stage the files (flag a file's changes to be saved to git) typing   git add . ;
    We can also type ou the full file names. "." will add the all;
- Commit (save files to git) the files to the repository typing   git commit -m "commit";
- Change files open atom in the repository directory  atom .   and change the files;
- Commit the changes git commit -m "commit";

### Remote - Github

- Create new repository going to https://github.com/ and logging in with your account;
- Click the new repository button in the top-right. "+" . Choose your repository name;
- Create your new repository and copy the link to the clipboard in ssh format;


### Local

- Add the github remote in your git repository folder typing:  
       git remote add origin git@github.com:USERNAME/REPOSITORYNAME.git;
- Push files to the remote repository typing  git push -u origin master.
- Next time just type  git push -u    to push files.
